The height of the large equilateral triangle is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} p,$ so the area of the large equilateral triangle is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} p^2.$  The height of each small equilateral triangle is $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} s = \frac{9 \sqrt{3}}{8} p,$ so the area of each small equilateral triangle is $\frac{9 \sqrt{3}}{32} p^2.$  Therefore, the total area of the four small equilateral triangles is $\frac{9 \sqrt{3}}{8} p^2,$ so the ratio of the total area of the four small corrals to the area of the new large corral is $\frac{\frac{9 \sqrt{3}}{8} p^2}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4} p^2} = \boxed{\frac{9}{2}}.$

